b'We asked our associates: What does Pride mean to you? "Pride to me means having the courage to be myself\xe2\x80\x94to not let\xc2\xa0my environment define\xc2\xa0who I am and what I believe. Pride\xc2\xa0to me means having the freedom to choose how I want to live my life,\xc2\xa0how I treat\xc2\xa0myself and how I treat others. Pride to me is being totally proud of who I\xe2\x80\x99ve been, who I am, and who I\xe2\x80\x99m becoming.\xc2\xa0Pride at my core means deeply understanding the dignity of life and the interconnectedness\xc2\xa0of all things." - Taisha'

b'We asked our associates: What does Pride mean to you? "As a gay man who grew up in the south, it was never easy, so for me, Pride holds a special place in my heart.\xc2\xa0 To me, Pride means accepting who you are and being proud of all you stand for. It is a moment to realize that you should never be ashamed of who you are and to celebrate the diversity, inclusion and accomplishments within the LGBTQ+ community. It is also a chance to bring awareness to the constant battle we fight for our rights. We will never stand down just because of who we are. In the words of our friend Lady Gaga, \'Don\'t hide yourself in regret, Just love yourself and you\'re set, I\xe2\x80\x99m on the right track, baby, I was born this way.\'" -Ashton'

b'We asked our associates: What does Pride mean to you? "Pride is being an ally for my LGBTQ+ family and friends by supporting, listening and loving them for who THEY are, while educating anyone that challenges their ability to live equally. My fundamental belief is being true to yourself is central to living a happy life, and no one has the right to take that away. Being an ally has meant providing a safe space and acceptance as the first person that a few people came out to in High School, bringing my cousin to his first youth LGBTQ+ event, supporting my best friend through his transition, and much more." -Jessica'

b'We asked our associates: What does Pride mean to you? "Pride month reminds us that we should all celebrate who we are and support our friends, family and colleagues in the LGBTQ+ community not just this month, but always.\xe2\x80\x9d -Chris'

b"We asked our associates: What does Pride mean to you? \xe2\x80\x9cPride is the collective power of unapologetic\xc2\xa0love. It reminds us that diversity is\xc2\xa0the heart of humanity and embracing our\xc2\xa0authentic selves is not only\xc2\xa0possible, but absolutely beautiful. 
June invites us to celebrate and\xc2\xa0learn, to have conversations and\xc2\xa0get lost in the best of Google rabbit\xc2\xa0holes.

It's far more complex to\xc2\xa0discuss coming out of the closet\xc2\xa0than cleaning the closet. I'm proud\xc2\xa0to design for a company that\xc2\xa0stands openly with Pride.\xe2\x80\x9d -Heidi"

b'We asked our associates: What does Pride mean to you? "Pride to me means remembering and being grateful for the LGBTQ+ community members and allies that came before me to pave the way for the freedoms and rights that I enjoy today. It is a time to come together and celebrate history and progress, but also an opportunity to reflect on the changes that must still come. Freedom is not a given for all and must be fought for; no one is truly free until all people are liberated. This Pride, I\xe2\x80\x99m reminded that we must all align our personal missions with those that work for racial justice and equality." - Greg'
